This group of borrowers consists of four members, led by S., 27, an unmarried tailor who owns a house economically constructed on land inherited from his parents. S. is famous locally for his ability to tailor modern clothes and his ideas for fashion models. He recently acquired a few apprentices to support and expand his business, and so is requesting a loan to buy two machines for them.<p> 

The other group members, all residents of Siem Reap Province, are: 

C., 25, who sells cooked ingredients and is requesting a loan to buy more products for her shop;

S., 30, who owns a general store and is looking for a loan rebuild her store;

D., 32, who earns a living by fishing and is looking for a loan to repair the fishing boat.

This five-member group of borrowers from Battambang Province, Cambodia, is led by Y., 49, a mother of three children, one  married and living separately, one learning to repair mobile phones, and one attending school. Y. produces Naem food (a roll made of hashed meat, usually pork, wrapped and cooked in banana leaves) for which she has many customers who buy from her in bulk. She recently developed plans to increase the size of her business, so she is now requesting a loan to buy hundreds of kilograms of pork for that expansion. <p>

The other four group members are: 

K., 46, who sells Naem food in her local village and is requesting a loan to buy a bicycle for her business;

Y., 50, who sells Naem food from his motorbike and is looking for a loan to buy more Naem food for his business;

S., 39, who sells junk food with papaya throughout the whole commune and is applying for a loan to buy more chairs and tables for her business;

S., 25, who sells Naem food and is asking for a loan to build a small store for her business.

Rubina baji, a resident of Vehari, Pakistan for the past 10 years, is married to A. U., a factory employee earning a monthly wage.  She is the mother of  three sons and one daughter, all students at a nearby school.<p>

Rubina baji is fully aware of the current world economic situation and the hardships everyone is undergoing.  Because it is not easy for a single person to bear all of a family’s living expenses, she helps her husband by selling clothes. She buys her inventory from the famous markets in Multan and Lahore and sells in her native city and local community. She is now applying for a loan to buy more clothes to expand her business. <p>

Rubina baji is the group leader of four other women from her community:
Irshad baji wants a loan to buy groceries for her grocery shop;
Shazia baji seeks a loan to buy washing powders and liquids for her laundry business;
Shaheen Akhtar baji is requesting a loan to buy lentils, cooking equipment and spices for her food business; 
Saima Hameed baji desires a loan to buy tools to repair electric items. <p>

This is a group loan. The loan funds will be distributed among the group members, each of whom will invest in her own business. The members mutually guarantee one another's loans, so if one member does not repay, the others are responsible.
